      "My first time seeing one of Nolan's films in the theaters, and all I can say is WOW. Nolan has truly mastered the art of SFX, this was the best theater-going experience I've had in my life. The big question is where does this movie fit in with other Nolan films? This is my 3rd Nolan review, and as I mentioned last time, I absolutely hate comparing his movies; it's an impossible task! I'm going to have to put it at position 3. behind Interstellar and Inception, and ahead of The Dark Knight Rises. This film had some of the most mind-blowing moments of any Nolan film. Yes, you heard me correctly: Tenet is significantly more mind-blowing and confusing than the likes of Memento, The Prestige, and Inception (I'm still debating whether Interstellar's big reveal is more or less mind-blowing than some Tenet moments). \n\nThere's no other way to describe this movie than Nolanesque: he leverages time to create a gorgeous plotline and story. No matter how many times Nolan uses the time to form a story, it never gets old. I mean just try and think how many times he's used time as a central backbone to his films! John David Washington, Robert Pattinson, and Elizabeth Debicki are on the top of their game throughout the entire film, creating some incredible scenes. There is only one slightly negative thing I have to say about the movie: the absence of Hans Zimmer. Don't get me wrong, I think Ludwig G\u00f6ransson is an awesome composer (I'm a huge fan of The Mandalorian soundtrack), but I just think Zimmer is better, and he knows exactly how to work with Nolan, as the dynamic duo have teamed up for the majority of Nolan's films. I highly highly recommend giving this one a watch (ok perhaps several watches). I know a lot of people haven't seen this since it's new, so I tried to not talk too much about the plot. As always, leave your own thoughts down below!\n\nEDIT (2/25/21): Just finished watching Tenet for the second time, and I HIGHLY recommend that everyone watches this film as many times as possible. There were so many new things I was able to catch, like the red tag on the agent\u2019s bag in the opening opera scene, Neil knowing exactly what drink to get for The Protagonist, the shipping crate marked with \u201cTallinn\u201d in the Oslo Freeport, I could go on and on. The profoundness of the time inversion is really what makes this film so incredible; especially with how the inversion makes for a beautiful (bittersweet) ending to a mind-blowing adventure. I can\u2019t give this film enough praise, it\u2019s just that good!",
