      "First Scorsese review! I wanted to do a 45th-anniversary review of Taxi Driver, but I looked it up and realized I missed it on Feb. 8th. I know you're probably wondering why I scored this movie a little low considering how it's typically very acclaimed by most movie critics. And the main reason I rated this movie at 79% is due to one factor that comes with watching this movie post-2019: The Irishman. I actually saw the Irishman before watching Goodfellas, and I noticed a ton of similarities; I mean obviously both were crime films directed by Martin Scorsese and had Robert De Niro & Joe Pesci playing major roles in the film. They both use the exact same style of narration: the main character (Henry & Karen Hill for Goodfellas, Frank Sheeran for The Irishman) narrates the story from the future, meaning they tell the story how they see it looking back at it. I think Martin's Scorsese's ability to make a good crime film actually improved over time, as I like The Departed and The Irishman better than Goodfellas. The reason is that they contain much more action than Goodfellas does. I know many people won't agree with my opinion, but I like a movie with more action, and that's how I feel.\n\nWith that being said let's take a look at what Goodfellas did right. It did a fantastic job of projecting Henry & Karen's emotions on to the audience; it made us feel all of the complex dilemmas and emotions they were going through during the film. One of the major premises of the film is focusing on how a crime family works. We saw the incredible loyalty and devotion associated with it. Especially after Karen & Henry get married, and Karen is roped into the family. And I think that's important to note, that the crime family really was a family! Throughout the film, we see many gatherings and dinners among the members. Henry and Karen's kids even refer to the crime boss, Paulie, as Uncle Paulie. On the other side of the coin, we have the negative aspect of loyalty, which is mainly shown with the murder of Pesci's character, Tommy, who got killed because he killed another \"made\" member of the family. \n\nSo yeah, this film did a great job of showing the deep complexities associated with crime families; I was just bored at some points during the film. That's the reason why I take The Irishman or The Departed over Goodfellas. And I get that Goodfellas intentionally is not supposed to contain much action, so it's kind of hard to directly compare to The Departed, but I made the comparison given that they're all Scorsese crime films.",
