      "I think it's about time we had some Tarantino on Adamovies, so here we go! I'm probably going to start to review his movies chronologically by release date with a few exceptions (I haven't seen Pulp Fiction because it hasn't been on Netflix yet). This review is going to serve also as an introduction to Tarantino as well as a review for Reservoir Dogs. Tarantino is notorious for his bloody, violent films. Every single one that I've seen so far has been at least somewhat violent (even Once Upon A Time... In Hollywood). He's even been quoted to say, \"Violence is one of the most fun things to watch.\" I would definitely say he does violence better than every other director ever. So that's a brief intro to Tarantino: violent stories, and Samuel L. Jackson.\n\nSo, now onto Reservoir Dogs. Currently, I can say with no hesitation that this is his worst movie in my opinion. As of writing this, I've seen Reservoir Dogs, Kill Bill: Volume1&2, Inglourious Basterds, Django Unchained, The Hateful Eight, and Once Upon A Time... In Hollywood. And I'd have to guess that I'd like Pulp Fiction better than this. Let's start with what I liked about this movie: the way the story was told. The story was told in an en media res style, where we're thrown right into an action scene, to begin with, and then we go back in time to examine the events that led up to the car chase. The other thing that was impressive was how low of a budget this film was shot on. This is impressive due to the cost to make vs. the success of the film ratio. \n\nMy main issues with this film are the story. I think that it lacked the usual Tarantino substance. It's a simple story: A crew of anonymous bank robbers is infiltrated by an undercover cop, so the diamond heist goes wrong, leading to casualties of both cops and bank robbers. I summarized the essence of the story in a sentence. Obviously, it's much more nuanced than what I said, as we go back in time to see what led to the robbery, but I really thought the film was lacking and a little boring in places. When compared to something like The Hateful Eight, which also has similar elements where the viewer is trying to figure out which character actually caused something, Reservoir Dogs doesn't do all that good of a job in blowing our minds with how it's revealed that Mr. Orange was an undercover cop.\n\nSo yeah, those are my brief thoughts on Reservoir Dogs: important because it was Tarantino's big break, but my least favorite of his work.",
