      "This year 2021 marks the 60th anniversary of a John Huston classic, The Maltese Falcon. This film follows Hollywood legend Humphrey Bogart playing a private investigator pulled into the twisted mess of three individuals all desperately chasing a fabled gem-encrusted Falcon. \n\nFrom the exposition of the film, with a murder only minutes in, the audience knows immediately that this story may not go how they expect. While the scale of the entire film is small, playing out entirely in a few select locations in San Francisco, the deep and complex plot is thoroughly developed by the stellar dialogue and pacing. All of the actors and actresses have incredible chemistry, and present flawlessly the interpersonal tension and atmosphere of each interaction. Each successive scene gives the viewer more insight into the frenzy to find the Falcon, and the steady addition of new characters throws consistent curveballs at the audience\u2019s prediction of what is really going on. Step by step, the introduction of acting legends Mary Astor as O'Shaughnessy, Peter Lorre as Mr. Cairo, and Sydney Greenstreet as \u2018The Fat Man\u2019 (important to note, an amazing performance for his first feature film role) adds character contrast and unpredictable behavior to each encounter. The viewer\u2019s expectations and guesses are constantly teased and played with, leaving the audience truly questioning until further information is revealed. The film advances in an interesting fashion, not developing characters always by actions that occur on screen, but by treading backwards and slowly revealing events that occurred leading up to the situations shown in the film. The end result is a dense, captivating film that packs sharp discourse and fantastic storytelling in barely over 100 minutes.\n\nIn summary, The Maltese Falcon is full of action, suspense, and dialogue which keeps you intrigued and constantly wondering what comes next. Incredibly well-written and beautifully shot, it is obvious why the film is critically acclaimed and regarded as a landmark Hollywood achievement, and one of the best films ever made. It is a workshop on mystery storytelling and how to keep an audience invested. For a film lover, this is simply a must-see due to its notoriety and legacy on the genre and film as a whole. If you\u2019ve seen it before or choose to watch it, I\u2019d love to hear your thoughts down in the comments section. ",
