    content:
      "Your Name, one film in a long line by director Makoto Shinkai, is often cited as his best work. Your Name tells the story of a teenage boy and girl who miraculously switch bodies with each other during the day, living the other person\u2019s life a few times every week. Even if you\u2019ve never seen a single Shinkai film, after watching Your Name you\u2019ll understand why it is his masterpiece. And if you have seen other Shinkai before, well, you\u2019ll understand too.\n\nThe story of Your Name is not irregular compared to other films by Shinkai. He has numerous Romance and Fantasy animated films, all with their own unique component, such as Weathering With You\u2019s meteorological superpowers or The Garden of Words\u2019s distinct scenery. In Your Name, the component itself is not even unique: stories involving characters \u2018switching bodies\u2019 have been seen multiple times before in cinema. Yet, Shinkai is the first to perfect it. Immediately, Shinkai throws us into the body-switching antics of main characters Taki and Mitsuha with effectively no buildup. The two, a few days a week, switch bodies and live the life of the other for the day, until they go to sleep. Shinkai makes these situations simultaneously comedic and dramatic, as silly moments where the characters discover the \u2018parts\u2019 of their counterpart pivot to moments of suspense where one does not know what the other said or did while in their body. Taki and Mitsuha have never met in person, but they communicate to one another by leaving notes while in the others\u2019 body. While the viewer might expect that they simply fall in love and meet each other in person, living happily ever after, they\u2019d be quite mistaken. The body-switching is only a launch pad for so much more. But, for the sake of the beauty of this film, I won\u2019t reveal any additional information here. If you\u2019re reading this before watching, I highly recommend going into Your Name with limited information beforehand, so I won\u2019t reveal too much more in this review.\n\nThe reason that this storyline is so amazing is because of the emotions it evokes from the viewer. Numerous times, moments switch from being heartwarming to heart-wrenching, from breathtaking to devastating. There are sections of absolute satisfaction and joy, but also periods of incredible dissatisfaction, with something so in reach yet so far away. The first sizable chunk of the film deals solely with the characters living in each others\u2019 bodies, which Shinkai uses as a tool to make the viewer emotionally invested in Taki and Mitsuha. Awkward encounters, surprisingly fortunate events, and humorously wild antics relate the audience to the two teenagers, building the connection to the viewer so you feel as strongly as the characters do as events play out later in the film. \n\nRegardless of the story, the animation is, simply put, sensational. It might very well be the most beautiful animation I\u2019ve ever seen come out of Japan (the only contenders being other Shinkai films or some of the Ghibli catalog). The character design, the meticulously detailed scenery, the lighting, all contribute to a brilliant and beautiful visual experience for the entire length of the film. In addition, the score does a fantastic job enhancing the visuals and the dialogue to further emphasize the emotions Shinkai elicits from the viewer.  \n\nIn summary, Shinkai has made a visual and narrative masterpiece with Your Name. Regardless of if Romance, Fantasy, or Japanese animation are your cup of tea, this film is highly worth the watch. As I said earlier, the best way to approach Your Name is with little information prior. If you can get it on a big screen, you\u2019ll be able to appreciate all the small visual details added in. Shinkai made no compromises with this film, and that shows in its flawless visuals and ability to evoke raw emotion from its audience. ",
