      "So I'm going to review Kill Bill in two parts, given that it was released as two separate films covering each of the two volumes. It's amazing to me how long the two of these movies are combined given the simple nature of the story: a story of revenge. Kill Bill is split into 10 chapters, with Volume 1 covering the first 5, and Volume 2 the second 5. I'll do more of an analysis on the whole story in my review of Volume 2, so let's start with the first 5 chapters.\n\nThe title of the film effectively lays out the entire backbone of the story: it's a revenge story, with the end goal of the protagonist (The Bride) being to kill Bill. I should mention that The Bride is one of my favorite main characters in any film I've seen; I've even spent a good hour or so trying to make a GTA Online avatar that looks like her. Throughout the 10 chapters, we tend to jump around in time a bunch, so I'll do my best to keep that straight for you all. The Bride used to be a member of The Deadly Viper Assassination Squad, which was headed by Bill. I won't get into the details, but Bill brutally betrays The Bride, leaving her in a coma for years, and upon waking up, The Bride wants nothing but vengeance. Given that the combined runtime of these two films is over 4 hours, it's really important that the exposition of the story provides a powerful reason for why revenge is needed: something that will keep the viewer invested the whole time. I can wholeheartedly say that this film does a fantastic job of this. \n\nI usually don't like to go too much into the plot, in case some readers haven't seen the movie, but I will just give a quick outline of the plot of the first volume: The Bride wakes up from a coma, and then goes on a MISSION to kill every last member of The Deadly Viper Assassination Squad. The majority of volume 1 focuses on The Bride's journey to kill O-Ren Ishii. What's really interesting is some different mediums of film used throughout volume 1. For example, chapter 3 tells the story of O-Ren Ishii as narrated by The Bride, and this chapter is all in an anime. I haven't ever really seen anime blended in with live-action before, so it was really cool to see. It made some of the violent scenes comical, as the blood would unrealistically spew like a fountain. \n\nThe highlight of both Kill Bill volumes, for me, comes in chapter 5, the end of volume 1. This is the epic showdown between The Bride (decked out in that awesome yellow jumpsuit from the movie poster), and O-Ren Ishii. The Bride uses her new Hanzo Steel sword to go ham on all of O-Ren Ishii's henchmen. This is one of the goriest scenes in any film, and it's really cool because some of the shots from the fight scene were in black and white to reduce the gore. Kill Bill: Volume 1 ends in the most epic way possible, with O-Ren getting \"a haircut.\"\n\nThe reason why I rated volume 1 higher than volume 2 was mainly because of this last fight scene - it was one of the best fight scenes in any movie. We'll pick up the rest of this story in the second review...",
