      "Here we are, the first Nolan film I've reviewed that isn't action or sci-fi! I'm not going to waste any time introducing Nolan or anything like that, since I've already reviewed a handful of his other films. If any of you haven't read any of my other Nolan reviews, just know that I'm a little biased because he is my favorite director by far.\n\nLet's dive right in. Two words I would use to sum this movie up are obsession and devotion. You'll have to watch this movie to know what I mean. This film tells the tale of 2 rival magicians who compete for attention and each other's secrets for how they perform tricks. It's set in Victorian London, but if I had to date it, I'd put it around the turn of the century (the 1890s). The reason for this is because of Nikola Tesla appearing as a character in the film (portrayed by Starman himself David Bowie!), although of course, this is fiction, so there's really no way of telling exactly. Even before I saw this movie for the first time, I knew I was in for a treat, I mean Nolan + magicians? That's a combo that could easily include some of the best twists and tricks for a film. And boy was I right, my very favorite part of this movie was this major twist at the very end of the film; the writing for the scene was so perfect.\n\nAs far as characters go, we have some really good ones. Christian Bale and Hugh Jackman portray the dueling magicians, alongside Michael Caine as the mentor figure (like he always is in any Nolan film). I really enjoy the way the story was told. The whole story is narrated by Michael Caine's character, Cutter, and the film opens chronologically towards the end, but then we make a jump back to the beginning of the story and proceed mostly chronologically from there. In addition, Nolan used a second storytelling device that I thought was really creative and brought 2 other (somewhat unreliable) narrative perspectives into view. What I mean by this was we also have part of the story told from the journals of Borden and Angier. What gets even more confusing is the two diaries were written very cryptically, as Border purposely tries to trick Angier at one point by letting him read his diary. I know it's confusing, and I didn't do a great job of explaining, but the main takeaway is the story is told in a purposely confusing manner, but it makes for an incredible viewing experience.\n\nAnd of course, as with all Nolan films, you can expect a fantastic ending, with a huge twist. It's so beautiful because the film is structured into 3 stages exactly like a magic trick: the pledge, the turn, and the prestige. So the ending of the film is like the reveal of the magic trick when you're in disbelief of what just happened, and it feels so awesome.\n\nSo yeah, I highly recommend giving this one a watch, as I do with all Nolan films. @ me in the comments with anything I missed, or with any additional thoughts you have!",
