    content:
      "Simply put, Junichi Sato\u2019s A Whisker Away does a lot of things right. It has interesting characters and an exciting plot, in addition to visuals, score, and voice acting to make it a great viewing experience. But, there are things A Whisker Away does that stop it from being great.\n\nThe primary draw of the film is, well, cats. The main character, Miyo, has obtained a method to turn herself into a house cat. Once in her feline form, she uses it to get closer to her schoolboy crush, Taro, who doesn\u2019t realize this friendly cat is one of his classmates. Later on, we learn her ability comes from a cat-shaped masquerade mask she obtained from the magical Mask Seller. He acts as a liaison between cats and humans, allowing either species to transform into the other with these masks. The central conflict comes when the Mask Seller wants to take away Miyo\u2019s humanity to sell it, and she would be forced to stay a cat forever, never to return to her human form. But, within all this plot, there are writing and concept choices that I find questionable. \n\nThe first noticeable thing when watching this film is the inspiration drawn from Spirited Away by Studio Ghibli. Not that this is a bad thing, because their filmography is renowned, but the choices on what to draw from feel odd. For one, the idea of the Mask Seller felt very similar to Yubaba in Spirited Away. The Mask Seller as an antagonist wants to keep Miyo as a cat forever, just as Yubaba wants to keep Chihiro in the spirit world. But, the Mask Seller effectively is just a worse, underwhelming, and one-dimensional version of Yubaba. The Mask Seller himself actually has almost no power; he is easily held down by a handful of cats. Throughout the movie he has no character development whatsoever, and has no intrigue as a villain. He\u2019s simply an annoyance, and adds almost nothing to the story as an entity. As well, the giant, floating, invisible tree that serves as the \u2018Island of Cats\u2019 resembles a mashup of Spirited Away\u2019s spirit world and James Cameron\u2019s Na\u2019Vi-dwelling Hometree in Avatar. Because they spend such little time there, it feels like an afterthought. I believe there was ample untapped potential to use the island as a much bigger plot device and setting, given how detailed and fantastical it briefly was. \n\nAnother large facet of the film that seems odd is the decisions characters make, most specifically the main character Miyo. First and foremost, I\u2019m not sure which writer wrote Miyo jumping off the roof of a two story building to stop some schoolboys slandering her crush. Why was that necessary or logical? On top of that, who wrote the constant harassment she gives Taro, not to mention the constant embarrassment she puts him under. Obviously the writers want to show that Miyo is young, ignorant, but has a passion for Taro. But her behavior feels forced and strange. The writers tried so hard to show she has a crush on him that it just comes across as odd and unrealistic. Other than matters involving Taro, her decision making throughout the entire film is questionable. There are numerous times that the central conflict could be solved instantly. Typically, this is not always a bad thing, but in the film it is so forced the idea that Miyo just doesn\u2019t quite understand the Mask Seller\u2019s intentions that it\u2019s almost painful to sit through. As a whole, Miyo is just plain stupid, irrational, and uncomfortable, thus the audience barely relates to her character or forms empathy for her struggle. \n\nAlthough my review is rather critical, the viewing experience is still positive. It has impressive visuals, a story that, at the minimum, keeps you somewhat invested, and wraps up nicely at its conclusion. There are just a few items that I question the decision to include in the film, and some adjustments that could be made to improve it as a whole. The best way to enter the film is not hoping to explore it too deeply, and just to enjoy it for what it is: a simple, fun-to-watch story of two kids, with a little bit of magic here and there. If you\u2019re already a fan of Japanese animation, then A Whisker Away is definitely worth the watch, but otherwise, take it for what it is.\n",
