    content:
      "Today we're going to be taking a look at James Cameron's sci-fi masterpiece, Avatar (yes, the one with the blue people). As you probably could have guessed by now, sci-fi is by far my favorite genre to watch, which is why I was super excited to get to review Avatar. There's really no other word I can use to describe this film other than monumental. In the future, I'm probably going to be diving into other older revolutionary sci-fi films, but for now, I'll get into why I think Avatar is one of the latest in the line of groundbreaking sci-fi films. The reason why is so simple: absolutely incredible CGI. I mean that's probably the biggest reason why this movie set so many box office records back in the day (well, this and the fact that it stayed in theaters for over half a year).\n\nI should mention that CGI is definitely a double-edged sword: if you do it wrong, people will tend to complain about it, but if you do it right, it makes for an incredibly immersive film that has the power to transport you into environments that aren't creatable just by shooting on earth. And this is really what I believe Avatar does better than almost any other CGI of its time, it was able to create a planet so unique and different from the earth that it had that incredible out-of-this-world immersive feel that captured audiences for the entire 2h42m runtime. Now not only is the entire environment CGI, but the Na'vi and the wild creatures are also all completely CGI. In my opinion, the best CGI is the kind where you can't tell it's CGI, and this is exactly what Cameron and his team nailed in this film.\n\nOk, so what else did this movie do right other than CGI? I'd have to say the score and the characters. To quickly mention the score, it was beautiful all the way through (google Avatar main theme to see what I mean). Zoe Saldana and Sam Worthington star alongside sci-fi legend Sigourney Weaver (Alien review coming soon, probably from legendary critic TrevorC), and all three of them absolutely nail the roles. \n\nGetting into the plot a little bit, the entire film is set on the planet Pandora, which is inhabited by the native Na'vi (the blue people). A big conglomerate from earth called the RDA set up mining operations on Pandora to mine an extremely rare and priceless called unobtainium (wow, nice name!). Of course, their mining operation is absolutely destroying the wildlife, sparking conflicts with the local Na'vi. The scientists working for RDA are trying their absolute hardest to resolve this conflict peacefully by transplanting their consciousness into Na'vi avatar bodies, but things get out of control when RDA's military wants to burn down the local wildlife, so obviously the scientists team with the Na'vi to stop them. The one negative thing I have to say about the plot was that it was very predictable. \n\nSo yeah, to sum this one up, it was an epic sci-fi adventure fueled by what I think is the best CGI to date (even after 12 years). Make sure to @ me in the comments to let me know anything I missed or just to drop your own thoughts!",
