      "At the time of this review, we\u2019re just weeks away from numerous award shows honoring films from 2020. Due to the nature of the pandemic, it has been hard to watch new release films either due to not seeing marketing or not wanting to head to the theater. The Trial of the Chicago 7 eluded my sights until I happened upon it on Netflix. Doing more research, I was intrigued to see it had received numerous nominations, including best picture, director, screenplay, on top of multiple awards for specific cast members. Thus, I knew I had to give it a chance. The film tells the story of the Chicago 7, a cohort of anti-Vietnam War protestors charged with conspiracy and crossing state lines with the intention of inciting riots at the 1968 Democratic National Convention in Chicago.\n\nThe first thing to note about this film is the casting: it\u2019s flawless. Each individual actor and actress perfectly embodies the role of their character, in physical appearance, behavior, and delivery. There is nothing I would change about the portrayal of the seven defendants, especially standout performances by Eddie Redmayne and Sacha Baron Cohen. Even beyond them, Frank Langella\u2019s performance as the commanding and prejudiced Judge Julius Hoffman grabs the audience in every scene he takes part in. And let\u2019s not forget Joseph Gordon-Levitt, whose polished performance as attorney Richard Schultz effortlessly makes the character\u2019s story dynamic and intriguing for the entire duration of the film. And finally, we must applaud Mark Rylance for his role as defense attorney William Kuntzler, perfectly playing a man fighting against a system that won\u2019t let him win. I can easily regard this film as one of the most well cast I\u2019ve ever viewed. Regardless of the story, I could thoroughly enjoy watching this movie just to see all the actors and actresses shine in their roles. \n\nIn regards to the plot, it is very well constructed. It is an interpolation of scenes in the courthouse, flashbacks in time, sections of Sacha Baron Cohen doing standup with jokes relevant to the current plot point, and back at the house in between trial days. Despite the vast amount of changes in environment, it never feels jarring or haphazard. Rather, having these constant switch-ups gave depth and detail to a story that seemingly would have less, given it\u2019s entirely about a single trial that has occurred because of a brief string of events. It\u2019s written to keep the audience engaged as we learn more about what led up to the trial, and does a spectacular job at it. \n\nAs someone who knew nothing about this trial beforehand (even being a Chicago native myself), I was intrigued to see how it would play out, and went to research more on it after viewing the film. Because it caused me to do that, the goal of this style of historical drama was successful, thus I would highly recommend it to anyone reading this. At the bare minimum, I give my recommendation so you can see why it is nominated for so many things, because it definitely deserves it.\n",
