      "Simply put, The Dark Knight is the greatest comic book movie ever made. It is difficult to attribute this to anything other than Heath Ledger's maniacal and Oscar-winning turn as the Joker. While he wasn't the first and won't be the last to take up the mantle of Batman's nemesis, Ledger will almost certainly go down in history as the definitive portrayal of the Clown Prince of Crime. Knowing what he endured for the roll and that he never got the recognition he deserved after his untimely death makes watching the movie even more of an emotional experience. \n\nWhile he rightfully garners most of the praise, Ledger is by no mean the only actor to put on a masterclass in this movie. Christian Bale is a delightful Bruce Wayne / Batman, and his chemistry with Michael Caine as Alfred is as strong as ever. Aaron Eckhart's portrayal of Harvey Dent is strong, and I particularly love the dry wit of Morgan Freeman's Lucius Fox. I could go on, but seemingly every character in this movie is compelling and portrayed extremely well. I love all the different interactions they are allowed to have, and the hospital conversation between the Joker and newly minted Two-Face remains one of the most haunting dialogue scenes I've watched. Speaking of haunting scenes, I have to mention the movie's take on the Prisoner's Dilemma with the two ferries. In a movie as batshit crazy (pun intended) as this one, that moment of hope in humanity was truly inspiring.\n\nI have nothing but good things to say about this movie. It resides in the very upper echelon of Nolan films, a prestigious distinction. Hans Zimmer provides an incredible score, and every actor puts on a performance for the ages. I've watched this movie a dozen times, and I imagine I'll watch it at least a dozen more. I'm sure I'll never get tired of it, because it's both the movie we deserve and the movie we need.",
