      "The hardest part about watching a less-known Hitchcock film is the inevitable comparison to the rest of his filmography. I\u2019ll be the first to admit I love his works, he\u2019s my favorite director ever. But how can an archaic thriller like Blackmail, the first ever British film with sound, stand up to the likes of Psycho, Vertigo, Rear Window, or any other number of Hitchcock\u2019s numerous thriller masterpieces? To combat this, we have to put it in context, both in terms of the era it was released in, and the point it is at in Hitchcock\u2019s career. The distinction I make with Blackmail is that it is a stepping stone; without it, those renowned, household-name films may never have come to full fruition. Thus, when analyzing Blackmail, we must take it for what it is: an early glimpse at a genius and pioneering filmmaker beginning to hone his craft.\n\nBlackmail tells the story of a woman, Alice, who kills a man who attempts to rape her. The woman\u2019s boyfriend Frank, a police detective, is put onto the murder case. Another man named Tracy, knowing information about the case, plans to blackmail them. As far as surface-level plot goes, that\u2019s pretty much it, except for some later developments I won\u2019t spoil here. It isn\u2019t until the movie ends and the viewer ponders for a bit that one can see the multiple levels Hitchcock was working on; blackmail is present far more than just on the facade. All of the characters are guilty in some way, and one could argue Alice, the person who actually committed the murder, is the least guilty of them all. Everyone except her is soaked with malicious intent. Will Frank counter-blackmail Tracy? Will Tracy blackmail more than just Alice and Frank? Will Frank blackmail Alice, considering their struggling relationship? The concept of guilt has no tangibility, it\u2019s one person\u2019s word against the other, and who\u2019s to say what is the truth? The scale of what plays out on screen is small, but part of the magic is how it leaves the viewer when it ends, pondering these questions of intent and guilt. \n\nIn addition to the intriguing story, Blackmail is overflowing with signs of Hitchcock. His positioning of the camera, both glaring and subtle symbolism, his portrayal of women, the concept of the spectator, distinct usage of light and shadow, and many more trademark ideas are present. The common \u2018seeing something you weren\u2019t supposed to\u2019 that is present in almost every Hitchcock thriller is front and center. Someone who has seen Hitchcock before could swiftly recognize Blackmail as his work. That is what makes it so great, viewing it over 90 years after its creation. It is young, 30-year-old Hitchcock stretching his wings, utilizing sound for the first time, piloting new techniques and building up his staples. It is an early signal pointing to him eventually becoming known as the \u2018Master of Suspense\u2019. Fans of the genre or of the master himself will enjoy Blackmail, at the very least as a time capsule of a director taking off into subsequent decades of masterpieces.\n",
