      "Silicon Valley is currently my favorite TV show, and I just finished watching it for the second time. This season really did a great job setting a premise for the rest of the show, and had a great storyline of its own. The main character of the show is Richard Hendricks, who begins the show working at Hooli, a giant tech company modeled after the likes of Amazon, Google, and Apple. While there, his side project, Pied Piper, is seen by Hooli\u2019s CEO, Gavin Belson, the primary antagonist of the first season. The software is discovered to have an incredibly efficient means of compressing data, which makes the software highly valued by Belson. He wants to buy it from Hendricks, however, Hendricks had shared it with a venture capitalist, Peter Gregory, and Belson and Gregory to wage a bidding war which concludes with Hendricks taking $200,000 from Gregory for 5% of the company. The rest of the season follows Hendricks and his friends, mainly two coders Dinesh and Gilfoyle and Richard\u2019s assistant Jared aka OJ aka Donald, as they cope with the problems of building a viable product, culminating in a startup competition where Hendricks has a breakthrough and writes new code which shatters the theoretical limit of compression, winning them the competition.\n\nThis season is one of the best of the entire show, and is also the only season to feature one of my favorite characters, Peter Gregory, whose actor passed away between seasons 1 and 2. One of my favorite things about this show is that it is relatively accurate to what it would actually be like to begin a startup in the Valley. The characters are all unique enough that the dynamics between them are fun to watch but also every character makes sense in their role. This show also does a great job of satirizing big tech throughout. For example, one of the running jokes is that whenever a new product is introduced, no matter what it is, those presenting it talk about how it will be used to \u201cmake the world a better place\u201d, even though all it usually ends up being is a computer program. Overall, this season was very fun to watch and made me really excited to watch the rest of the show.\n",
