      "I'm back again reviewing one of my favorites (surprise surprise). This review is probably going to sound kind of similar to the one I did for Avatar, but it's because I think they share a lot of the same strengths. I'm definitely not going very far into the plot here, because I think most people know at least a little bit of what happens in this film. Anyways, a quick summary of this one is billionaire John Hammond builds a theme-park on an island name Isla Nublar, which is about 120 miles west of Costa Rica. He recruits two paleontologists to come to review his work, which was the resurrection of dinosaurs through DNA strands that were preserved for millennia inside of amber. And as you might have guessed, everything goes wrong when a massive storm hits the island, and dinosaurs are on the loose. As wonderfully stated by Ian Malcolm, \"Life finds a way.\"\n\nThe reason why this movie is one of my favorites is primarily for 2 reasons: the concept, and the score. The concept of resurrecting dinosaurs is not only fascinating, but it seems almost believable, especially with how far biological engineering has come in the past 28 years since this film was released. Spielberg does a tremendous job of capturing the audience and bringing them into this frightening world where dinos roam free alongside humans. I love how deep that concept is, that two species separated by millions of years walk on earth simultaneously. Not only did Spielberg nail this profound concept, but his execution of roping the audience into the fear of coming face to face with dinos is brilliant. One very famous example of this from this film is having water ripple whenever a T-Rex is nearby due to the shockwaves produced by the massive footsteps. It's these little things that pull you in and capture your attention for the entirety of the film.\n\nThen, I'm sure you all saw this coming, but I have to mention the score. As I mentioned in my review of Batman Begins, the Spielberg and Williams duo is my second favorite director-composer combo in history. Williams' work on Jurassic Park is some of his best in my opinion. If I had to rank it against his other notable scores, I would say it's 3rd, only trailing Star Wars and Indiana Jones. The Jurassic Park main theme is one of the most memorable and beautiful tracks from any movie and is one of my favorites.\n\nSo yeah, there are my quick thoughts on a classic. Another thing I forgot to mention is how interesting it is that the \"bad guy\" of this movie is nature. It's a cool concept and something that is not done a lot in movies. As always, @ me down in the comments with anything I missed, or your thoughts!",
