      "Manhunt: Deadly Games tells the story surrounding Richard Jewell and the 1996 Atlanta Olympic Park Bombing, and the hunt for the bomber. Not only does this show provide entertaining, engaging content that had me finish the entire series in two days. If you aren't familiar with Richard Jewell, he was a security guard at Centennial Olympic Park on the night of the bombing, and was the one who found the bomb and alerted others, saving countless lives. However, the FBI believed that Jewell fit the profile of a hero bomber, and that he planted the bomb himself, only to gain fame for discovering it again. This was leaked to the press, and the media, eager for a story, pushed the narrative despite no conclusive evidence, disrupting Jewell's life in ways he did not deserve. The plot of this show was incredibly gripping, with lots of unexpected twists and turns, and it brings to life the events within the FBI, Jewell's personal life, and the media that occurred over 20 years ago during the investigation. The manhunt that occurred to find the real bomber was exciting to watch and kept me glued to the screen. Beyond the entertainment value, I applaud the makers of the show for demonstrating the power of false information, and the harmful consequences of pushing a narrative about someone just because it is convenient and will get views. The show portrays Jewell in the way he deserves to be portrayed: a hero, and even with all the great entertainment value and plot, this is what I enjoyed most about Manhunt: Deadly Games.",
