      "Man, was I disappointed by this movie. Ready Player One is my favorite book of all time, so I came into the movie with high hopes, despite hearing the movie wasn\u2019t very faithful to it. They completely butchered the storyline of the book to make it more accessible to the average movie viewer and in doing so, removed a lot of the things that made the book great. One of the defining characteristics in the book is a myriad of 80\u2019s references and callbacks that pull the whole thing together. They modified, or in many cases completely changed, so much of the book that it is barely recognizable. This leads to an extremely rushed and weak plot written with seemingly minimal effort . Add subpar acting and unconvincing dialogue and you end up with this movie. It is very hard to believe that this movie was directed by Spielberg.\n\n\tDespite my many criticisms, the movie was not entirely bad, which is why my score is still above 50. The visual scenes are incredible, with several impressive character avatars and multiple exciting action scenes. The overall concept of the film, which comes from the book, is still great. It takes place in the not-too-distant future, with the real world completely devastated by unspecified events. To escape this dismal reality, everyone spends the majority of their time in the OASIS, the first virtual simulation capable of accommodating anyone and everyone who wants to join it. The founder of the company who built it, James Halliday, dies and leaves behind him a treasure hunt, with the winner taking over ownership of the OASIS and the over $250 billion he made from it. The main character, Wade Watts, who goes by Parzival online, leads a group of his friends to victory over a huge corporation who wants to win and completely change the OASIS to make money.\n\n\tIf you have never read the book, I would probably suggest watching the movie if you can ignore the horrible character development and cringy lines said by many of the characters. If I hadn\u2019t read the book and loved it so much, I likely would have enjoyed this much more. However, this is the first time I have actually been mad at a director for making a movie, simply because I know the potential of the story and hate to see how badly they mutilated it.\n",
