      "All right, so here is my overall review for WandaVision season 1! This is going to be a very short wrap-up since I did reviews for every individual episode of the season, so if you're curious about more specific details, definitely go check out my episode-by-episode reviews! For me, this show really serves as a benchmark for the future of Marvel shows. This is the first one that was designed specifically for Disney Plus, and I think it was a really good start. A good analogy is that WandaVision is Marvel's version of The Mandalorian (only I like The Mandalorian a good deal better than WandaVision in my opinion). The MCU had been super movie focus, so this show was really a transition into the TV show scene. I think they made the transition pretty well, migrating many beloved characters such as Wanda Maximoff, Vision, Darcy Lewis, and Agent Woo over to this new sphere. I think this really was a unique concept, and it was super meta having a TV show within a TV show. With that being said, I think the show got off to a slow start. We didn't see any action happen until the very end of episode 3! Looking back at the show as a whole, the story looks super stretched out. What I mean by that is I really think they could have easily told that story with enough detail in 6-7 episodes versus the 9 that they chose to go with.\n\nHowever, once the show got rolling, it definitely got better. Not only that, but we were introduced to a few new notable additions to the MCU with grown-up Monica Rambeau and Agatha Harkness. I really hope we get to see more of Agatha in the future because I thought her character arc was very short-lived in this show. As for Monica, we know we're going to see more of her in Captain Marvel 2, so that's good news. The show leaves the future of both Wanda and Vision a mystery, so we'll have to see what happens with them in the future. As of the time I'm writing this, there is no confirmation of a WandaVision season 2, so I guess we'll have to wait and see how their character arcs are finished.\n\nNow that we have The Falcon and The Winter Soldier coming out in a couple of weeks, we kind of know what to expect now thanks to WandaVision setting a benchmark for future MCU shows. Obviously, WandaVision's concept was super unique, and I'd expect The Falcon and The Winter Soldier to be much more combat-based (which I'm really looking forward to), but at least we can expect to see many familiar faces from the existing MCU, and also some new ones.\n\nSo yeah, I really enjoyed going episode-by-episode, and I plan to do it again in 2 weeks with The Falcon and The Winter Soldier. If you finished WandaVision, make sure to @ me in the comments with your thoughts!",
