    content:
      "It\u2019s fair to say I had high expectations going into this film. I had just watched the first Wonder Woman (which is a great movie) less than two weeks prior to refresh my memory, and now Christmas Day had arrived and the world premiere for WW84 was upon us. I had watched Pixar\u2019s Soul earlier that morning, which was fantastic, and had high hopes that Christmas would go 2-for-2 on great premieres. So to say Wonder Woman 1984 was disappointing is not exactly an understatement, but more not precisely what I\u2019m trying to say. It wasn\u2019t just disappointing, it was plain awful. \n\nEverything compelling about the first movie was sadly absent from the second. Rather than a powerful and driven female protagonist, we got a whining Gal Gadot that couldn\u2019t move past her previous film\u2019s trauma, and a Kristen Wiig side character that was simultaneously conniving, attempting to be quirky, and just plain stupid. Rather than a nefarious and omnipotent God of War antagonist like the original, we got the goofy and erratic businessman Maxwell Lord who grants wishes like a genie in a bottle. While the premise of a wish-fulfilling megalomaniac had neat moments, it created a story where Wonder Woman couldn\u2019t actually fight the main villain. He\u2019s not a combatant, he\u2019s just a normal guy, thus their final confrontation was simply boring. Instead, we were stuck watching Diana get beat up by Kristen Wiig, including watching a Cats-musical-inspired animal/human combo version of Wiig fight Diana in likely the worst lighting and choreography for a final fight scene I\u2019ve ever witnessed. Other than these few scenes, the movie has a surprising lack of action sequences, especially compared to the first Wonder Woman. This means most of the story is character interaction, but unfortunately, the writing of all the characters is confusing and strange, with the dialogue feeling unnatural and the interactions feeling forced. No amount of great acting by some the cast could make up for the abhorrent script. This is further compounded by the fact the movie is over two and a half hours long, stretching out bad scenes and dialogue much longer than they need to be.\n\nWithin WW84 itself, there are numerous more issues in story writing, the first of which being Chris Pine literally possessing an innocent man\u2019s body. Diana wishes him back to life, yet he has to inhabit the human body of another man, whose family and friends seemingly forget he exists. Diana sees no problem with basically eliminating an innocent man from existence for her dead boyfriend. And speaking of Chris Pine, somehow the knowledge he gave Diana about how planes fly was enough for her to learn how to fly herself. And no, I don\u2019t mean in a plane or with a wingsuit. Wonder Woman literally flies, sometimes with her arms out like wings on a plane, and other times in a Superman-esque pose. Is it a bird? Is it a plane? No, it\u2019s Diana having her own version of flight school while the world goes to shit back on the ground. This flying section was entirely meaningless and a waste of time, and simultaneously messes up the DC film universe canon. She never utilizes this useful skill in any other DCEU film. Maybe DC will find a way to retcon this later, but for now we're left confused why they even gave her this ability. \n\nSpeaking of canon, as an entry in DC\u2019s extended universe of films, WW84 managed to introduce plot holes to the entire universe. First off, was it not an entire point made in Justice League that after Chris Pine died, she stayed to herself and didn\u2019t reveal herself to the world, hiding in secret amongst the world of man? Yet, in the first few minutes of WW1984, we see her fighting petty thieves in a crowded mall, swinging around like a dollar-store Spider-Man in full view of hundreds of civilians. The film implies that she has done this multiple other times too. Additionally, in the other DC films we get the impression that Diana had not seen Chris Pine since he died, but clearly that is untrue given she saw him fairly recently in 1984, when she briefly brought him back to life. Don\u2019t get me wrong, I grew up watching and reading much more DC shows/comics than Marvel, but I think DC should take some tips from Marvel and have better continuity between films in their own universe. The DCEU has so much potential, but they\u2019ve continued to find ways to screw it up. \n\nOverall, WW84 had potential. Just a few actions could drastically solve many of its issues: reduce the runtime to about two hours or less, change most of the dialogue, rewrite some larger plot points, and then you\u2019ve got a movie at least half as good as the first Wonder Woman. Patty Jenkins proved she could direct a great action movie with WW84\u2019s predecessor. But, as it stands, if Maxwell Lord offered me a wish, I\u2019d ask to have back the two and a half hours of Christmas Day I spent watching this mess.\n",
