      "In a shocking turn of events that nobody saw coming, the first Harrison Ford film I'm reviewing is not Star Wars! Today, we're going to be looking at The Fugitive. This one should end up being a relatively short review, as I really don't have too much to say about it. To give a super quick plot summary without spoiling too much, basically, it's a classic tale of a man being falsely accused of murder, and uncovering the truth and evidence to prove his innocence. So this movie wasn't doing anything revolutionary with the story, but the execution of this well-worn tale was pretty excellent in my opinion. With the Feds constantly on Richard Kimble's tale, there's always the risk of being captured around every corner, which provides for that exciting thrill that I look for in any good action-thriller. I really do think it was important to nail the execution of a story of this type since it's done a lot in movies. If this was just some repeat of any other murder story, I definitely would have rated this much lower.\n\nWith that being said, I can't really give this an outstanding rating because it doesn't bring anything new to the table for me. Simply put, it's a good movie; just not anything thing to be stoked about. In addition, I think the reason why my rating might appear harsh is because of the evolution of technology, and the fact that I watched this as a 19-year-old in 2021. These types of \"eluding capture\" movies from decades ago seem so far-fetched to me now, because of how good technology is nowadays. In today's day and age, it would be so much harder to elude capture for as long as Richard Kimble did in this story. And I know it's not this movie's fault, but it's just harder for me to go along with the story when I know how fictional this kind of thing would be today. For that reason, I think my review will be lower than an older audience, as the events of this movie would likely seem way more plausible without all of the tracking tech we have today.\n\nSo yeah, I did enjoy the execution of a classic style of a thriller, but my enjoyment really doesn't go much beyond enjoying seeing Harrison Ford in a classic movie. It should be interesting to see the contrast between this review and the review I write on Indiana Jones. If you've seen this movie, @ me in the comments and let me know what you thought!",
