      "@Trevor: 76%\n@brendanmwagner: 78%\nMe: 80%\n\nAlright, so today we're kicking off our set of Marvel reviews with Captain America: The First Avenger. We're going to go through all of these in chronological order in the MCU timeline because we thought that would be more fun than just going chronological by release year. We thought that this one ranked in the middle of the pack; certainly not the worst, but certainly not the best. This one most appropriately fits into the category of origin story within Phase 1. I'll briefly address the plot, as at this point, I doubt I'm spoiling or ruining anything critical for anyone. \n\nSo this story follows Steve Rogers on his journey to becoming Captain America. I mentioned that this was the first one chronologically, and that's because it's actually set in the middle of WWII. Steve gets chosen to get a dose of serum from the lead Allies Scientist, and it instantly makes him grow close to a foot and put on like 80 pounds of muscle. Steve eventually goes over to Europe and goes head to head with Red Skull, the leader of the radical Nazi advanced science and weapons division named Hydra (more of them in a future review). Captain America leads a band of soldiers and they start beating up on Hydra all across Europe, taking out their weapons factories. On one of the missions, Cap's best friend Bucky Barnes falls out of a high-speed train in the Alps and falls to his death(?). I also forgot to mention that Steve falls in love with one of the heads of the Strategic Scientific Reserve, Peggy Carter. In the finale of the movie, Red Skull is attempting to go and bomb the entire US with a futuristic plane powered by a blue energy cube called the Tesseract (more on this important energy supply soon). Cap ends up defeating Red Skull, and Red Skull gets sucked into the Tesseract and vanishes. The futuristic plane is still carrying a bunch of warheads, so Cap has to put the plane down in the middle of nowhere to avoid people dying. Finally, we cut to the future where Cap awakens after being frozen in ice for 70 years because apparently this somehow kept him alive? It's a little questionable but it's all for a story so I'm ok with it. Director Nick Fury of S.H.I.E.L.D. greets Cap and lets him know that he's been frozen for 70 years. To recap where this movie leaves us, Captain America wakes up 70 years from his last memory, realizing that all the friends he once had were dead.\n\nThe thing with this movie is there's nothing that special to it other than a solid action film. That's why all 3 of us rated it lower than most other Marvel films. Especially when you compare it to another origin story film like Ironman, it's just not as interesting. What this movie did do was serve as most of the historical basis for the rest of the films, as the Strategic Scientific Reserve turns into S.H.I.E.L.D., we learn the origins of Hydra, we learn what the Tesseract is, and how Captain America is out of place in the future. The remaining films in the timeline build heavily on the Tesseract, S.H.I.E.L.D., and Hydra, so this was an important film in setting up the future of this universe. I just thought it was a little bit bland compared to some of the successors of this film.\n\nSo yeah, I'm not saying this movie was bad by any means, I just don't think it stands up to the likes of other stronger MCU films like Ironman, The Avengers, or Guardians of the Galaxy, etc. I know everyone has so many different opinions on Marvel movies, so make sure to comment on what you agree with. This was already mentioned in an announcement, but to reiterate, the Adameter for all Marvel movies is a simple unweighted average of @Trevor's, @brendanmwagner's, and my own ratings. We thought this would standardize all of the ratings. There are still 20+ more of these to come, so stay tuned in the coming weeks! Next up is Captain Marvel from legendary reviewer @Trevor!",
