      "@brendanmwagner: 87\n@Trevor: 83\n@BulkyEndymion38: 83\n\nIron Man was a fantastic introduction to the MCU and definitely started it off with a huge bang that left a lot for the following movies to live up to.  We get to follow the story of Tony Stark (MIT represent!), a wealthy genius whose family business profits off of war by building weapons of mass destruction and selling them to the military.  Stark never really cared about that until he was almost killed by his own tech when he was kidnapped by the leader of the terrorist group.  The leader told Stark he could escape if he built the terrorists his newest weapon, but Stark knew he was lying.  With the help of Dr. Yinsen, he instead built a suit out of metal scraps he was given, and became Iron Man.  He broke out of the lab and escaped into the desert after Yinsen heroically sacrificed his life for Stark.  Once Stark got back home, he pledged that his company would no longer build weapons and would shift their focus to other things.  As you may assume, the rest of the owners of the company were not too happy with this and tried to circumvent him.  However, Stark was too busy trying to build a better Iron Man suit to really focus on that until it was too late.  The movie culminated in a big fight between Stark and Obadiah Stane, the other main owner of the company.  Stane had secured the technology of the early suit from the terrorist group and used it to build his own massive suit, which Stark was barely able to defeat.  \n\nThis movie set a high tone for the MCU and I really think that without this movie being as good as it was, the MCU would not be where it is today.  The first end-credit scene in MCU history features Nick Fury introducing Stark, and us, to the idea of a coalition of heroes called the Avengers.  This movie distinguishes itself from many of the other intro Marvel films with its use of humor to make the movie more relatable, which became a hallmark of the MCU.  The villain is complex and interesting and the main character himself develops throughout the film as he works to build the suit not for personal gain but to protect others.  When Stark reveals himself, he uses the iconic line, \u201cI am Iron Man.\u201d which makes a reappearance in Avengers: Endgame, making for a fun callback that does a great job of tying together the beginning and end of the original wave of heroes.  This film performed very well commercially and showed that there was a large audience for this kind of movie, encouraging Marvel to continue to expand the universe, with Tony Stark becoming many people\u2019s favorite superhero.\n\nNext up in the MCU review series is Iron Man 2, which will also be reviewed by me.\n",
