      "@brendanmwagner: 84\n@Trevor: 75\n@BulkyEndymion38: 84\n\n        Iron Man 2 did not quite live up to its predecessor, but it is still a very enjoyable film that I had a great time rewatching.  Robert Downey Jr. returns as Tony Stark, but this time, everyone knows that he is really Iron Man.  Near the beginning of the film, we see Ivan Vanko, the disgruntled son of the scientist who helped Howard Stark build the arc reactor, come to take revenge on Stark for his father\u2019s lack of recognition for his work.  This comes while Stark is driving in the Monaco Grand Prix, and he is barely able to escape until he retrieves the Iron Man suit.  In the aftermath of the first movie, everyone in the world saw the potential for a powered suit and as a result, lots of hostile organizations tried to replicate it.  However, no one is successful until two different things fall into the lap of Justin Hammer, the CEO of a rival company.  First, Rhodey takes one of Stark\u2019s suits to the government after Stark has a drunken party which ends with the two of them fighting.  Hammer is hired to outfit the suit by the government.  Hammer also breaks Vanko out of prison to help him build his army of drones.  However, while Hammer is demonstrating his tech at the Stark Expo, Vanko takes over and tries to attack Stark.  After Stark and Rhodey, who have reconciled, destroy all of the drones, Vanko himself shows up and the two of them beat him as well.  This movie also sees the introduction of Black Widow, who has several of the impressive hand-to-hand combat moments which will become her hallmark.\n\n\tWhile this was still a very enjoyable film, it failed to live up to the highs of the first film.  Since this one doesn\u2019t need to go into any of the backstory that the first one needed to cover, you would think that there would be a more complete and full plot.  However, the first one still has a better villain and conflict, while the sequel often seems predictable and rushed.  Another conflict which arises, Stark\u2019s blood toxicity rising from his chest implant, is rather lazily solved and is pretty unrelated to the rest of the movie.  I really enjoyed this film, but it is hard to not compare it to the first movie.  There are plenty of good things about Iron Man 2, such as the further development of such characters as Pepper Potts and Rhodey, both of whom become much more important to the MCU, especially Rhodey as War Machine.  We get to meet Phil Coulson and Nick Fury and learn about the Avenger Initiative.  There are plenty of the Iron Man one liners that make him such a fun character, and the action scenes are very fun to watch.  Overall, I think this movie is overhated by many Marvel fans simply because it doesn\u2019t quite live up to its potential.\n\nNext up in the Marvel series is Thor, reviewed by the illustrious @BulkyEndymion38.\n",
