      "@Trevor: 70%\n@brendanmwagner: 69%\nMe: 68%\n\nOk, so we've arrived at our first Thor movie! For this one, we all were very close to the same score, averaging out at 69%. I'll get right into a super quick summary of the movie. Thor is about to become King of Asgard, but after a rash and unauthorized attack by Thor, his father Odin, the current King of Asgard (played by Anthony Hopkins aka Dr. Lecter), banishes him to earth to learn how to be \"worthy\" of his power. While on earth, Thor meets Jane Foster, an astrophysicist, who helps him on his journey to find his hammer and return to Asgard. Thor's older brother Loki is super jealous that Thor is getting the throne, so we realize that it was his plan all along to get Thor banished so Loki could take his father's place as King. Loki tries to kill Thor, but in doing so, Thor becomes \"worthy\" by protecting the people of earth from Loki's giant robot, meaning Thor got his powers back and could return to Asgard.\n\nSo I should mention that I saw The Avengers before I saw Thor, and it's so funny to me how different both Loki and Thor are in Thor. What I mean by that is both of them seem so much more childish, and even though the main point of Thor was Thor actually maturing a ton, he's basically a different person at the beginning of this movie versus when he appears in The Avengers. Same with Loki, he just seemed so much more \"evil\" to me in The Avenger than in Thor. I should also mention that I'm not the biggest Thor fan, I just don't think he's all that interesting of a character to me. The only time I've really enjoyed Thor is in Thor: Ragnarok, but I think that's mostly due to Taika Waititi's incredible directing in that film. While we're on the topic of directing, I had no idea that the director of Thor was Kenneth Branagh, whom you may know as Andrei Sator, the villain from Tenet, or Commander Bolton from Dunkirk (yup, I love making even the smallest connection to Nolan films).\n\nSo yeah, this wasn't a terrible movie or anything, I just don't find the Asgardian fantasy element all that interesting. If I had to pick the best thing about this film, it would be Loki. This was Loki's birth into the MCU, and he is such an interesting character to me. I think part of it is that Tom Hiddleston is a much better actor than Chris Hemsworth in my opinion, but Loki's mischief and tricks are always very amusing to watch, which is why I'm super excited to watch the new Disney+ show Loki, which releases in about 2 months (which I will be going week by week on). \n\nNext up in the Marvel Series is The Avengers, review by @Trevor!",
