      "This movie was definitely one of the most interesting films I've seen in the last few months. It's been on Netflix for a little while now, so I thought I'd give it a try considering it's Scorsese + DiCaprio. Similar to The Silence of The Lambs, I'd definitely throw this movie into the Psychological Thriller category. I can't really go into the plot very deeply at all, because that would ruin so much of the film because that's just the way this movie works.\n\nTo start off, we're dropped right into a scene with US Marshal Teddy Daniels and his new partner Chuck. They're en route to Shutter Island, which is located in Massachusetts and houses a mental hospital. They were called there to investigate the mysterious disappearance of inmate Rachel Solando, who vanished mysteriously from her cell. Soon after, we realize that Teddy is a classic example of an unreliable narrator, as he experiences frequent hallucinations and visions. Teddy and Chuck soon expand the investigation to try and figure out some of the mysteries hidden behind the scenes as Shutter Island, which is what the majority of the film revolves around.\n\nThat summary was super general, but the best part of the movie was certain reveals in the plot, so I really don't want to give much of that away. So this movie has a 2h19m runtime, and I'd say up until maybe 1h30m, I would have rated this movie in the 60% range, but the second half of the movie was so good, that it bumped up the score dramatically. I was so confused about what the heck was happening in the first part, and felt myself wondering, what even is the point of this story; where is it going? But I can surely say that the confusion of the first half is needed to make the second half as strong of an ending as it was. I absolutely love movies with big reveals, realizations, and twists. I've mentioned it in a few other reviews, but it makes the movie so much more interesting when your mind gets blown by new details you sort of did/didn't see coming.\n\nThe only reason why I didn't rate this one higher is it's such a weird and strange film to me (well mainly the first half, but definitely overall as well). During the first half, I was a little bit bored and sometimes question what I was watching. Now that I think about it, I felt a very similar feeling when I watched Taxi Driver for the first time, which is another Scorsese film from 1976. In both Shutter Island and Taxi Driver, there were so many moments where I was like what the heck am I watching right now. Don't get me wrong, they're both different films, but I definitely remember feeling very confused and weirded out in a similar manner.\n\nIn terms of where this stacks up with other Scorsese films, definitely not my favorite of his work, as I enjoyed The Departed and The Irishman a lot more. I get that these two crime films are drastically different from Shutter Island, but I can confidently say they're way better films overall.\n\nSo yeah, those are my thoughts on this strange thriller, but make sure to leave your own thoughts in the comments below!",
