      "Today is May 4th, 2021, so you better believe I'm going to write the first Star Wars review today. It may not be apparent yet since I haven't done any Star Wars reviews yet, but it's undoubtedly my favorite film franchise of all time. Star Wars is what I grew up on; Lego Star Wars: The Complete Saga, Star Wars: The Clone Wars, and Star Wars Legos themselves were all staples for fun for me (and still are to this day). Unlike most other reviews, I'm not going to give much of a summary at all, but rather spend time talking about why this is such a good film.\n\nThe Story: A New Hope follows a classic example of a story called the monomyth, or the hero's journey. You can look that up if you don't know what it is, but basically, it's a very traditional way of telling a story, and a method employed by a ton of other movies and books (Harry Potter, and The Lord of the Rings to name a couple). One might argue that it's not a very creative way of telling a story, but I think having a simple delivery of the story works very well for Star Wars, considering the creativity comes from the sci-fi nature of the film.\n\nThe Imagination: We have to take a minute to appreciate just how incredible and innovative this movie was for 1970s sci-fi. This truly was the most revolutionary movie for sci-fi ever created. Not only did George Lucas have the imagination to come up with the extraordinary details, but the execution to make them come to life. I mean think of how many things are unique to this movie: the conflict between the Rebellion and the Empire, the entirely new planet system (Tatooine, Dantooine, Alderaan, and the moon Yavin IV were among the ones mentioned in A New Hope), the tech and weaponry (the stormtroopers' E-11s, the rebels' DH-17s, Han Solo's DL-44, the Death Star, TIE Fighters, TIE Interceptors, TIE Advanced, X-Wings, Y-Wings, The Millenium Falcon I could go on and on and on about all the super-specific and detailed ships and weapons and tech introduced just in this first movie). It's also crazy how elaborate and drawn out the universe was even from the very start! Ben Kenobi mentions the Clone Wars in the first 40 minutes of the movie! This is something that would later be covered by 2 entire movies (Episode II and III), and a 7-season TV show, and somehow George Lucas was able to come up with it all the way back in 1977. I mentioned earlier how good the execution of this creativity was, and I really mean it. One of the things this movie does best really making the audience feel like this really was filmed in a galaxy far far away. An example I love is in the very opening shot of the film, with Vader's Star Destroyer in hot pursuit of Leia's Tantive IV. This shot looks so real, like both of them are absolutely massive spaceships in real life. It's nearly impossible to tell that George Lucas actually filmed this shot with small-scale models of both ships. I also love this shot after watching Rogue One, because we know have a backstory to this conflict that we were previously thrown into without knowing, but now we know that both ships just jumped out of hyperspace, both having left the airspace above Scarif.\n\nThe Score: Finally, this movie got its own original score, and it just so happens to be one of the most famous movie soundtracks in history, composed by the legendary John Williams. I mean so much of the beauty of Star Wars comes from the fusion of its story with the music. I mean imagine Darth Vader without his own menacing theme. Imagine Luke staring into the two suns on Tatooine without the swells of Binary Sunset playing. It just adds so much character to this already amazing film.\n\nSo yeah, those are my super quick thoughts on this film, and why I think it truly is one of the best sci-fi movies of all time. I mean this is more than just a film, it's its own universe, beloved by people across the world. As I mentioned before, there are so many things I missed in this review. I simply don't have the time to detail all of my thoughts on this movie because I have so many of them. I'll definitely be working on expanding Adamovies' collection of Star Wars reviews over the next few months, and you better believe that I'll be tuned into The Bad Batch tonight, so you can expect a season 1 review on that whenever the show finishes.",
