    content:
      "It's been a while since our last Tarantino review, so what better time than now to review Pulp Fiction! I just finished watching it today, so this will all be with a fresh perspective. Pulp Fiction is a classic Tarantino film, told with a non-linear timeline, from multiple points of view. The main characters are hitmen Vincent Vega and Jules Winnfield, who work for a crime boss named Marsellus Wallace, and we follow them through a very very messy day at work let's say. We also have another separate but highly intertwined storyline going on that follows Butch Coolidge, a boxer who was just paid off by Marsellus to throw a fight. The other main player in this film is Mia Wallace, Marsellus's wife who Vincent has to take care of one night when things don't go according to plan let's just say. I won't go too much into detail in the plot because you really have to see the movie to understand all of it.\n\nWhat's good about this movie? First off, this film has so many notable hilarious quotes, including one which I consider to be quite possibly the funniest movie quote I've heard, \"Oh man, I...,\" and I won't finish the rest of the quote because it would ruin the entire scene. Secondly, I absolutely love non-linear and non-chronological storylines. Especially ones that start and end at the same time chronologically, and Pulp Fiction both starts and ends at the same diner scene from two perspectives, which I absolutely loved. Finally, the characters are super interesting, and they all have a depth to them that we explore throughout the film.\n\nThere's not much that I don't like about this film, but if I had to pick the biggest reason why I gave this an 82% instead of a 92%, it's most definitely because of how over-the-top extreme some of the scenes were, especially with all the drugs and such. I personally prefer a heavier emphasis on the action, which is why this film is falling below most other Tarantinos in my own opinion. Don't get me wrong, this is still a super interesting film, and I'm glad I watched it, but unlike Kill Bill or Once Upon A Time... In Hollywood, I'm not dying to watch this again anytime soon.\n\nSo where does this stack up against the other Tarantinos? I have a few other Tarantinos posted on the site already, but I can also compare it to the ones I've already seen but have yet to review. I definitely like this one better than Reservoir Dogs and The Hateful Eight, but it definitely falls short of Kill Bill: Volume 1, Kill Bill: Volume 2, Once Upon A Time... In Hollywood, and Inglorious Basterds. The jury's still out on which is better between this film and Django Unchained.\n\nSo yeah, those are my brief thoughts on this classic Tarantino film. If there's anything I missed, make sure to let me know in the comments below!",
