    content:
      "Today is June 12th, 2021, meaning Raiders of The Lost Ark, aka Indiana Jones 1, aka Raiders was released exactly 40 years ago today! We'll be diving into a super brief look at one of my favorite adventure films on its 40th birthday. This review is going to sound very similar to the Star Wars review, as it should since both of these franchises were my favorites when I was younger. In fact, Lego Indiana Jones was the first game I got for my Nintendo DS Lite. Anyways, I'm going to break down this one in a similar fashion, dividing it into 3 main categories.\n\nThe characters: While I don't think Harrison Ford is one of the most talented actors ever, I think Indiana Jones is his best character. He's intelligent, cocky, charismatic, and daring, so practically everything anyone would want in an action hero. Supporting him is Marion Ravenwood, who helps Indy along his adventure, fulfilling the sidekick role of the hero's journey/monomyth that I talked about during Star Wars. Finally, Belloq is the perfect adversary for Indy, as he sports many of the same personality traits that Indy does, with the addition of greed which eventually led to his demise. These core characters lead to an incredible adventure.\n\nThe score: There's not much to say here; it's the Williams & Spielberg duo back at it again, so the score perfectly suits the film, providing suspense when needed, and otherwise delivering a general sense of \"adventure\" if that makes any sense. If you haven't heard this soundtrack, you definitely have, you just didn't know it was from this movie.\n\nThe adventure: This is by far the best element of this movie in my opinion. The rich adventure aspect this movie delivers is unparalleled. The amount of lore and mystery that Spielberg chooses to surround the ark with builds so much excitement in the audience. In addition, the film travels to so many distinct locations, for example, the South American jungle and Cairo.\n\nSo yeah, those are my brief and quick thoughts on Raiders on its 40th anniversary. I quickly wanted to mention the ending of the film also, which was awesome. The ending of the film shows US government workers sealing up the ark in a wooden crate, and wheeling it into an enormous warehouse with thousands of identical-looking crates presumably containing similarly dangerous items. This uncertain note to end on was so cool to see. Anyways, if I missed anything leave it down below, thanks!",
